ce:section.ce:para:
Full characterization of CD ENPs is presented in Kamrani et al., 2017. Briefly, CDs are nearly spherical particles with a number average core diameter measured by TEM of 5.5 ± 0.1 nm (within the range 2–10 nm) and a z-average hydrodynamic diameter of measured by DLS of 20 ± 5 nm. The higher z-average hydrodynamic diameter compared to the number average core-diameter can be due to: 1) double layer thickness which is taken into account in the hydrodynamic diameter but not in the core diameter, 2) the bias in the z-average hydrodynamic diameter measured by DLS to larger size due to the distribution weighing; that is intensity-weighted hydrodynamic diameter compared to number-weighted core diameter (Baalousha and Lead, 2012). CD surfaces were rich in functional groups such as COH (hydroxyl), CH3, 
                        CH2, COC (ether), CO (carbonyl). The dissociation of these functional groups gives rise to CD surface charge. The zeta potential of CDs was negative at all experimental conditions (Table 3
                        ). CD zeta potential decreased (more negative) with the increase in pH due to higher dissociation of functional groups, and increased (less negative) with the increase in ionic strength due to surface charge screening by counter ions (Table 3). CDs have an absorption peak at 335 nm.
